As a human being with an open-minded, call me so. I believe every single person in this world has his/her/"they" (who can't be categorized) own purpose and meaning in this life. Some people has religions to "guide" them/ to "help" them to find their purpose, some people use their intuition and some people just walk freely without worrying anything. It's their rights to do so. But, some people believe what they belief is the "right" guidance to seek the purpose in this life. I won't blame them for what they believe. But, we need to consider that we live in this planet with more than just one religion. There are plenty of religions in this world. There are thousands of ethnicities in this world. .
Why do I write about it? Because I want people see from other perspective, that the world is too big for those who thought that what they believe is always right.
.
For me, I do have religion but, as a human being I also believe that every human being in this world has their own rights. AND AS A HUMAN BEING, I DON'T HAVE ANY RIGHTS TO JUDGE YOU FROM ANY PERSPECTIVE. NO MATTER what is your religion/ ethnicity/nationality/race/skin color/gender/or even your sexual orientation, for me you deserve to live this life, you deserve to be accepted for who you are. Even if there's no one support you right now, hang on there. There'll be people who accept you for the way you are. Just keep smiling, face the tough life and kick their ass who underestimate you!!!
.
By writing this caption, I'm ready for whatever you thought and whatever you write in the comments.
.

"Batman and Religion: A History" - A Creature of Logic and Science: 
Most of the modern Batman stories play to the concept of the Caped Crusader lacking faith or being an atheist or an agnostic. Whether it be his background in science or simple as having god like allies by his side, this constantly defies the idea of there being one God. There have been times where Batman has questioned his own disbelief in a higher power. One example is in Judd Winick's "Under the Hood" originally published in Batman (Vol 1) 635-641 illustrated by Matt Wagner and Doug Mahnke. As Black Mask takes control over Gotham City's criminal underground, his drug dealing business is being threatened by the Red Hood. As seen in issue 639 from June 2005, when Batman has suspicions that Jason has in fact come back from the dead, he becomes obsessed trying to explain this phenomenon. Batman talks to Zatanna about Ra's al Ghul's Lazarus Pits and if they can bring people back from the dead. When she says she's heard that's not possible, he needs to know if it is "theory or fact". He then speaks with Jason Blood, the alter ego to Etrigon, The Demon, who tells him there are many (dangerous) ways to raise the dead. Batman then travels to Star City to visit Green Arrow, who he knows has died, gone to heaven and was brought back to life and asks him if he was involved in the occult of any kind for this to happen. The logical being he is, Batman's search for answers eventually leads to Superman in issue 640. In Metropolis, Batman asks Superman about his return from being "dead" and wants more answers. Confused, Superman is concerned about Batman's need other answers than the ones he witnessed himself and not everything is "science". Batman replies "it has to be for me" and that he's "always had the facts". Any other reasoning from god to magic is just "another realm's science" but Jason's return has shaken the Dark Knight to his logical core. Even when Bruce faces Jason in issue 641, his rational thinking will not allow him to believe this was due to God, even though he himself cannot explain it. "Under the Hood" illustrates a true struggle of a non-believer trying to understanding the afterlife.
